\begin{abstract}
We construct a family of $6$-dimensional compact manifolds $M(A)$ which are simultaneously diffeomorphic to complex Calabi-Yau manifolds and symplectic Calabi-Yau manifolds. They have fundamental groups $\mathbb{Z} \oplus \mathbb{Z}$. Their odd-dimensional Betti numbers are even, and they satisfy the hard Lefschetz property. However, $M(A) \times Y$ are not homotopy equivalent to any compact K\"{a}hler manifold for any topological space $Y$.
\end{abstract}





\section{Introduction}
A K\"ahler manifold is a symplectic manifold together with a compatible complex structure. People have been interested in searching examples of compact complex or compact symplectic manifolds which are nonk\"{a}hler. In the 1940s, Hopf constructed complex manifolds $S^{1} \times S^{2N-1}$ ($N>1$) that are nonk\"{a}hler because their first Betti numbers are odd. Nowadays such complex manifolds are called Hopf manifolds (\cite[p.\ 14]{morrow_kodaira}). By similar reasons, it is easy to construct many compact complex nonk\"{a}hler manifolds. On the other hand, it seems more difficult and hence more interesting to find the symplectic counterparts. The existence of compact symplectic nonk\"{a}hler manifolds had been an open question for many years until Thurston (\cite{thurston}) discovered the first example. From then on, there has been many works on the symplectic part (see e.g. \cite{cordero_fernandez_gray}, \cite{fernandez_leon_saralegui}, \cite{gompf}, \cite{mcduff}, \cite{park}, and \cite{tralle_oprea}). In recent decades, people have been particularly interested in constructing complex or symplectic nonk\"{a}hler manifolds satisfying an additional condition, the Calabi-Yau property (see e.g. \cite{akhmedov}, \cite{baldridge_kirk}, \cite{bogomolov}, \cite{fine_panov1}, \cite{fine_panov2}, \cite{friedman}, \cite{goldstein_prokushkin}, \cite{grantcharov}, \cite{guan1}, \cite{guan2}, \cite{gutowski_ivanov_papadopoulos}, \cite{lu_tian}, \cite{smith_thomas_yau}, \cite{torres_yazinski}, and \cite{tseng_yau}).

In this paper, we will construct a family of $6$-dimensional compact smooth manifolds which are simultaneously diffeomorphic to complex and symplectic manifolds. They are Calabi-Yau in both the complex sense and the symplectic sense. We call these manifolds complex-symplectic Calabi-Yau. Notice that our meaning of ``complex-symplectic" is different from the concept ``holomorphic symplectic" (see \cite{guan1}). A holomorphic symplectic manifold is a complex manifold endowed with a holomorphic symplectic form. A holomorphic symplectic manifold certainly carries both complex and symplectic structures and is Calabi-Yau in either sense. However, holomorphic symplectic manifolds are always of real dimension $4n$, and hence never of dimension 6.

The examples in this paper are interesting to us because they share many properties with compact K\"{a}hler manifolds. However, they are nonk\"ahler in a strong sense. Before we state our main result, we need to make the word ``nonk\"ahlerness" precise. For a manifold $M$, the works in the literature usually interpret nonk\"{a}hlerness in one of the following ways.
\begin{enumerate}[\hspace{0.6cm}(i)]
\item $M$ is not homotopy equivalent to any compact K\"{a}hler manifolds.

\item $M$ is not homeomorphic to any compact K\"{a}hler manifolds.

\item $M$ is not diffeomorphic to any compact K\"{a}hler manifolds.

\item $M$ is not biholomorphic to any compact K\"{a}hler manifolds.

\item $M$ is not symplectomorphic to any compact K\"{a}hler manifolds.
\end{enumerate}
Here, (iv) also means that $M$ does not carry a K\"{a}hler structure compatible with its complex structure; and (v) also means that $M$ does not carry a K\"{a}hler structure compatible with its symplectic structure. Clearly, (i)$\Rightarrow$(ii)$\Rightarrow$(iii)$\Rightarrow$(iv) and (v). The nonk\"{a}hlerness of our examples is in a sense even stronger than (i).

Let us focus on the nonk\"{a}hlerness in the sense of (i) for now. Many works to prove a manifold being nonk\"ahler in the sense of (i) are to show the manifold does not satisfy one of the following properties.
\begin{enumerate}[\hspace{0.6cm}(a)]
\item Fundamental Groups: Only a small class of groups, named K\"{a}hler groups, can be realized as the fundamental groups of compact K\"{a}hler manifolds. (See e.g. \cite{A_B_C_K_T} and \cite{burger} for a survey.)

\item Betti Numbers: The odd-dimensional Betti numbers of compact K\"{a}hler manifolds are even (\cite[p.\ 117]{griffiths_harris}).

