Each $Y_i$ defined as above is called an exceptional divisor in $K$.

\begin{rmk}\label{holomorphic_symplectic_form}
It is well known that every Kummer surface $K$ is Calabi-Yau (see \cite[p.\ 241]{Barth_Peters_Van de Ven}), which means that its canonical line bundle $\mathcal{K}_{K} = \bigwedge^{2} \left( T^{*} K \right)$ is holomorphically trivial. Hence there exist holomorphic symplectic forms, i.e. non-degenerate holomorphic $2$-forms, on $K$. In fact, we can give an explicit description of such a form. Let $(z_{1}, z_{2})$ be the standard coordinate of $\mathbb{C}^{2}$. Then $dz_{1} \wedge dz_{2}$ is a holomorphic symplectic form on $T$. Since $dz_{1} \wedge dz_{2}$ is invariant under the $C_{2}$ action, it descends to a holomorphic form on the regular part of $\bar{T}$, which we also denote by $dz_{1} \wedge dz_{2}$. One can easily check that $dz_{1} \wedge dz_{2}$ extends to a non-degenerate holomorphic form on $K$. Denote this holomorphic symplectic form by $\varpi$, and denote its real part by ${\operatorname{Re}} \varpi$. Then $K$ is a real symplectic manifold with symplectic form ${\operatorname{Re}} \varpi$.
\end{rmk}

\begin{rmk}
A Kummer surface $K$ carries many real symplectic forms compatible with its natural complex structure, which define K\"{a}hler structures on $K$. However, ${\operatorname{Re}} \varpi$ is not such a form. We shall exclusively consider the symplectic structure $(K, {\operatorname{Re}} \varpi)$ of $K$ throughout this paper.
\end{rmk}

\begin{prop}\label{proposition_kummer_SCY}
The symplectic manifold $(K, {\operatorname{Re}} \varpi)$ is integrally Calabi-Yau. In other words, $c_{1} (K, {\operatorname{Re}} \varpi)= 0$, where $c_{1}(K, {\operatorname{Re}} \varpi) \in H^{2}(K; \mathbb{Z})$ is the 1st Chern class of $K$ with respect to the symplectic structure ${\operatorname{Re}} \varpi$.
\end{prop}
\begin{proof}
Since $\varpi$ is holomorphic symplectic, the structural group ${\operatorname{Sp}} (4, \mathbb{R})$ of the tangent bundle $(TK, {\operatorname{Re}} \varpi)$ can be reduced to ${\operatorname{Sp}} (2, \mathbb{C})$. Here ${\operatorname{Sp}} (4, \mathbb{R})$ and ${\operatorname{Sp}} (2, \mathbb{C})$ are the real and complex symplectic groups respectively.
Therefore, the conclusion follows from the fact that ${\operatorname{Sp}} (2, \mathbb{C})$ is simply connected.
\end{proof}

